1
00:00:00,537 --> 00:00:17,111
Namo Tassa Bhagavato Arahato Sambha Sambhudassa Namo Tassa Bhagavato Arahato Sambha Sambhudassa

2
00:00:17,867 --> 00:00:31,080
Namo Tassa Bhagavato Arhato Sama Sambuddhasa Homage to the Buddha, the blessed, noble and fully self-awakened one.

3
00:00:33,542 --> 00:00:35,585
This is my New Year address.

4
00:00:37,286 --> 00:00:40,911
So I'd better make it good, what do you think?

5
00:00:40,930 --> 00:00:42,112
This could ruin my future.

6
00:00:45,454 --> 00:00:47,216
I'd better get it spot on.

7
00:00:48,225 --> 00:01:04,109
So I suppose one thing that is good to do is just to, as it were, revise all the teachings we understand and know and just see if we can give ourselves some sort of direction for the next year.

8
00:01:13,644 --> 00:01:16,308
One of the major...

9
00:01:17,689 --> 00:01:42,617
factors in our progress spiritually is to be able to discern what is unskillful from what is skillful from what is wholesome from what is unwholesome and that discernment where does it come from what's this what is making the discerning who's who's discerning or what is what is that's discerning

10
00:01:43,710 --> 00:01:58,700
So we have to be very clear as to what the human being is made up of and then, as it were, see where the problem lies and then see how we can sharpen our sense of discernment.

11
00:02:00,022 --> 00:02:04,352
In the Buddhist teachings, we're made up of three aspects.

12
00:02:04,855 --> 00:02:08,622
Three parts or three vortices.

13
00:02:08,762 --> 00:02:10,245
Well, no, let's forget that.

14
00:02:10,525 --> 00:02:12,127
Just three parts will do.

15
00:02:12,147 --> 00:02:14,733
So first of all, there's our physical nature.

16
00:02:15,614 --> 00:02:18,318
And there's the mind, which includes the heart.

17
00:02:19,121 --> 00:02:22,205
Remember, our culture sort of split them apart.

18
00:02:22,388 --> 00:02:32,044
apart from each other, but the mind meaning our emotional thought, the emotional thoughts, the mental states that we go through.

19
00:02:32,384 --> 00:02:36,992
So don't forget, whenever we talk about, when I talk about mind, I'm always including heart.

20
00:02:37,653 --> 00:02:40,138
If I talk about heart, I'm centering on the emotional thing.

21
00:02:42,622 --> 00:02:48,092
So, and there's this nirvana dhatu, this element of nirvana, you see.

22
00:02:48,663 --> 00:02:54,229
which makes it very spiritual, very, very, I mean, what is it, this Nibbana Datu.

23
00:02:54,991 --> 00:03:03,442
So, our practice is to begin to observe all that's going on inside us.

24
00:03:06,385 --> 00:03:15,598
And in that observation, we access within ourselves this, the observer, the feeler, the one who knows.

25
00:03:17,062 --> 00:03:22,127
And in so doing, we are objectifying everything that we are experiencing.

26
00:03:26,012 --> 00:03:34,020
And this observer, the one who knows, is this satipaṋña.

27
00:03:34,161 --> 00:03:35,923
That's why I call this place satipaṋña.

28
00:03:38,306 --> 00:03:46,294
This is the Buddha within, and it's trying to isolate that from everything that it's experiencing.

29
00:03:46,342 --> 00:03:49,324
which is the process of awakening.

30
00:03:50,526 --> 00:03:52,106
What does this awakening refer to?

31
00:03:52,167 --> 00:03:54,770
It's simply awakening to the way things really are.

32
00:03:55,169 --> 00:03:59,674
That's the Buddha's little pet phrase, to see things as they really are.

33
00:03:59,693 --> 00:04:06,920
In fact, I was going to translate that sentence, that little phrase, literally it would be to see how things have come to be.

34
00:04:06,941 --> 00:04:14,407
So in other words, the Buddha's intimately involved in, wants us to become intimately involved in process,

35
00:04:15,417 --> 00:04:17,720
How do we create the world that we live in?

36
00:04:20,343 --> 00:04:32,538
Now, that separation within us when we become the observer, the feeler, the one who knows, the one who's experiencing within ourselves.

37
00:04:35,362 --> 00:04:40,569
What it's telling us is that everything that I'm aware of, I can't be.

38
00:04:40,589 --> 00:04:44,714
So the perceiver cannot be the perceived.

39
00:04:45,353 --> 00:04:49,158
In the same way that you perceive me, I can't be you.

40
00:04:49,178 --> 00:04:56,069
So as soon as you've turned something into an object, you've created a dislocation.

41
00:04:58,151 --> 00:05:09,487
So I'm still inside myself, thinking of myself, feeling myself, knowing myself as the observer, the feeler, the one who knows.

42
00:05:11,240 --> 00:05:23,112
So even at that point, there's some sort of reflection coming back to this essential knowing of its own existence.

43
00:05:24,153 --> 00:05:26,076
Just like when you look into a mirror.

44
00:05:27,937 --> 00:05:31,040
See, the face that you're seeing is not the face as it is.

45
00:05:31,221 --> 00:05:32,182
It's a mirror image.

46
00:05:33,122 --> 00:05:34,264
But it's still telling you.

47
00:05:34,324 --> 00:05:36,026
It's still looking in the right direction.

48
00:05:36,086 --> 00:05:37,266
It's looking back at you.

49
00:05:38,668 --> 00:05:38,749
See?

50
00:05:40,112 --> 00:05:46,858
Now, the paradox is that we'll never be able to see our own faces.

51
00:05:48,440 --> 00:05:49,362
Which is a terrible thing.

52
00:05:51,483 --> 00:05:54,745
We can see everybody else's face, but I can't see my own.

53
00:05:55,307 --> 00:06:03,274
I've got to use mirror, I've got to use some sort of ploy to make myself... And that will never be the face as it really is, although I might get very close to it.

54
00:06:03,574 --> 00:06:07,317
But the point is, I won't have a direct experience of what my face looks like.

55
00:06:09,052 --> 00:06:11,855
This tells us something about this quality of knowing.

56
00:06:13,619 --> 00:06:15,141
The knowing can never know itself.

57
00:06:17,403 --> 00:06:20,627
Just as the face can't see itself, the eye can't see itself.

58
00:06:21,228 --> 00:06:22,649
The tongue can't taste itself.

59
00:06:23,190 --> 00:06:30,459
If the tongue had a taste, say a curry taste, it'd ruin the ice cream, wouldn't it?

60
00:06:30,480 --> 00:06:30,560
See?

61
00:06:30,579 --> 00:06:34,745
So it's recognizing that all these sense bases are completely empty.

62
00:06:35,064 --> 00:06:38,790
They're empty of what it is they're to be sensitive to.

63
00:06:39,833 --> 00:06:51,790
And that's also true of this level of awareness, satipaṁya, that itself is completely empty, except it has attitude.

64
00:06:54,153 --> 00:06:55,956
It definitely has attitude.

65
00:06:56,978 --> 00:07:08,355
And this attitude has arisen because of some wrong understanding that what it experiences is itself.

66
00:07:09,466 --> 00:07:14,913
Now, if you go back to the birth, our birth into life, that's pretty understandable, isn't it?

67
00:07:15,454 --> 00:07:27,252
I mean, we came, we arrived, even in the womb, there's some consciousness, but we arrived and we're bombarded with all this sense data.

68
00:07:27,973 --> 00:07:32,360
And it's understandable, isn't it, that we presume ourselves to be that.

69
00:07:32,920 --> 00:07:34,223
We don't have that self-aware.

70
00:07:34,262 --> 00:07:34,983
We don't even have

71
00:07:35,334 --> 00:07:59,031
a sort of understanding but unfortunately it does create the delusion that I am this body, this mind, this heart and our process is to undermine that delusion by relocating the sense of self that's your first step so often when we are in pain

72
00:07:59,331 --> 00:08:04,240
if we get lost in the pain, if we're overwhelmed by the pain, then you become the pain.

73
00:08:04,721 --> 00:08:08,307
You lose a sense of somebody suffering pain, you're just in pain.

74
00:08:09,069 --> 00:08:14,639
So you stub your foot on the pavement or something, just for that little moment of ouch, you are that pain.

75
00:08:15,038 --> 00:08:22,351
So what identity means is a loss of any self-awareness into what it is you're experiencing.

76
00:08:23,733 --> 00:08:29,521
And this can be done at a physical level through these things like dangerous sports.

77
00:08:29,961 --> 00:08:34,086
I mean, that's one of the kicks of dangerous sports, that you get lost in it.

78
00:08:34,167 --> 00:08:38,634
And just for that one moment, you are totally in that mental state.

79
00:08:39,033 --> 00:08:39,654
And it's great.

80
00:08:43,019 --> 00:08:46,264
But it is an identity with our physical form.

81
00:08:47,493 --> 00:08:52,138
At a much more regular level is the identity we have with our emotions.

82
00:08:52,158 --> 00:08:58,563
So very quickly we can find ourselves being angry, being angry, being depressed.

83
00:08:59,225 --> 00:09:02,927
It's very easy for us to fall into that identity.

84
00:09:03,448 --> 00:09:09,254
And even more easy is, of course, thought patterns, where you find yourself just daydreaming, right?

85
00:09:09,274 --> 00:09:10,676
Especially when you're sitting.

86
00:09:10,696 --> 00:09:12,937
Just the mind shoots off and you're off.

87
00:09:12,957 --> 00:09:14,580
One of my favorite places, Acapulco.

88
00:09:15,285 --> 00:09:18,513
And then you suddenly realize that you've been away.

89
00:09:19,475 --> 00:09:21,779
What does it mean you've been away on a daydream?

90
00:09:22,422 --> 00:09:27,613
You've actually been the daydream in terms of your experience during that time.

91
00:09:27,653 --> 00:09:29,037
That's what you were.

92
00:09:29,076 --> 00:09:33,767
Now, as soon as we.

93
00:09:34,168 --> 00:09:48,645
come out of that and we diligently note what it is that's driving that thought, some sort of excitement for that perhaps, and we come into the body and we feel the excitement, immediately we've objectified things.

94
00:09:49,767 --> 00:09:52,649
As soon as you objectify things, it can't be the subject.

95
00:09:54,272 --> 00:10:01,019
So unwittingly, whether you know it or not, we are constantly undermining that sense of self.

96
00:10:02,350 --> 00:10:28,408
as something other so the body or emotions or thoughts by coming back to the position of the observer the feel or the one who knows you're undermining all those identities and that's the negative side the positive side is you are re-identifying with this observer now

97
00:10:30,599 --> 00:10:34,342
That mistake that we make of selfing, right?

98
00:10:34,363 --> 00:10:36,625
So the self is always arising and passing away.

99
00:10:37,606 --> 00:10:38,927
But the identity is the same.

100
00:10:39,207 --> 00:10:44,274
You're still identifying with the body, even though the body is offering you different experiences.

101
00:10:44,413 --> 00:10:48,818
You're still identifying with the heart, even though moods change, et cetera, and the mind.

102
00:10:50,279 --> 00:11:00,471
That process of this intuitive awareness becoming what it experiences is that falling into the delusions

103
00:11:06,221 --> 00:11:10,727
That's what we mean by delusion.

104
00:11:11,929 --> 00:11:32,937
And when we come out of that and there's a doubt about things, when there's a feeling of not knowing and we're into that state of a sort of wondering, but if there's some sort of fear or anxiety about a loss of identity, this is an extremely good sign.

105
00:11:33,644 --> 00:11:41,110
Because the one thing the self knows about itself but can't face is its own mortality.

106
00:11:42,451 --> 00:11:52,240
So every time you have a little hiccup of fear, of not knowing who you are, why you are, that's a sign that something is being undermined.

107
00:11:52,259 --> 00:11:53,701
That's good fear.

108
00:11:53,721 --> 00:11:54,702
There's bad fear.

109
00:11:54,783 --> 00:11:56,543
Bad fear is paranoia.

110
00:11:58,105 --> 00:12:03,009
But the sort of little shock that you get, for instance, I'm sure you've all woken up

111
00:12:03,445 --> 00:12:04,947
in a friend's house or in a hotel.

112
00:12:05,628 --> 00:12:08,471
And just for that, as you wake up, you don't know who you are.

113
00:12:08,491 --> 00:12:09,553
And there's that little panic.

114
00:12:10,134 --> 00:12:10,775
Have you all had that?

115
00:12:11,135 --> 00:12:11,616
Yeah, I see.

116
00:12:13,259 --> 00:12:21,370
That's that prior, just that moment prior to the panic was a moment of enlightenment, inverted commas.

117
00:12:21,871 --> 00:12:28,221
Because just for that one moment, you didn't know who you were and you were okay with it, but you couldn't stay there.

118
00:12:28,240 --> 00:12:31,225
You had to reach out and grab some sort of definitions.

119
00:12:31,879 --> 00:12:34,683
And so there's this moment of panic and then suddenly you realise, oh, it's me.

120
00:12:36,405 --> 00:12:37,668
And then it disappears.

121
00:12:37,707 --> 00:12:38,729
You're happy again.

122
00:12:41,552 --> 00:12:46,600
Now, what then are the definitions of a self?

123
00:12:46,620 --> 00:12:51,246
When you say, I am a self, what are the definitions?

124
00:12:51,267 --> 00:12:54,851
These boil down to the three characteristics.

125
00:12:55,712 --> 00:13:01,059
So the first one is this sense of permanency.

126
00:13:03,065 --> 00:13:11,594
Even though we know the body's changing, even though we know the world's changing, we know everything's changing, but there's something in me, this sense of me, doesn't change.

127
00:13:12,014 --> 00:13:12,796
I'm always there.

128
00:13:13,255 --> 00:13:15,398
Whenever I'm aware, I'm always there.

129
00:13:16,759 --> 00:13:22,625
And there's no definition, there's no definition to the me, apart from feeling that I am here.

130
00:13:23,086 --> 00:13:25,830
So there's a constant, yeah?

131
00:13:25,850 --> 00:13:28,032
Except, of course, when you fall asleep, then it disappears.

132
00:13:28,471 --> 00:13:32,716
But when you wake up again, here I am again, or...

133
00:13:33,743 --> 00:13:34,563
Not you again.

134
00:13:35,345 --> 00:13:36,745
It depends on your mood.

135
00:13:37,147 --> 00:13:41,471
So you've got this sense of me that continues.

136
00:13:41,831 --> 00:13:46,457
And that's where the delusion of impermanence is to be really found.

137
00:13:47,479 --> 00:13:54,907
And this sense of permanency is then displaced on the world itself.

138
00:13:55,248 --> 00:13:57,250
So how long is a moment?

139
00:14:00,594 --> 00:14:01,455
How long is a moment?

140
00:14:01,856 --> 00:14:31,341
hold on how long do you experience a moment the mind's very clever it's pretty long isn't it don't you think I mean things are changing but the mind holds it long enough to give you a sense of permanency somewhere that a moment isn't just a flash it's actually long enough for it to become real inverted comma is that right yeah see

141
00:14:31,894 --> 00:14:40,524
So this sense of permanence actually permeates, excuse me, permeates the very way we experience life.

142
00:14:41,684 --> 00:14:53,177
And what our practice is doing is constantly, or not constantly, but making us center as much as we can on this impermanency.

143
00:14:53,697 --> 00:15:00,264
And that's one of the reasons in this particular technique, Mahasi technique, that we go very slow, because the slower you go,

144
00:15:00,817 --> 00:15:07,207
the more the mind goes slow, the more you can see this process of impermanence.

145
00:15:09,049 --> 00:15:24,354
Now, that process of seeing impermanence can go to the point where you actually do experience, as you said, Sita, a moment of consciousness.

146
00:15:24,374 --> 00:15:27,298
So now, what then is consciousness?

147
00:15:28,325 --> 00:15:34,610
These words, by the way, you know, they're all over the place these days because they're studying it.

148
00:15:36,211 --> 00:15:38,033
So there's hundreds of definitions.

149
00:15:39,195 --> 00:15:44,500
Consciousness in the Buddhist teachings, as I understand it, is a screen.

150
00:15:45,039 --> 00:15:50,565
It's a multi-dimensional screen that holds emotions, thoughts, and etc., etc.

151
00:15:51,505 --> 00:15:56,931
And it flashes, it catches something, and it holds it long enough for it to be known.

152
00:15:58,817 --> 00:16:12,722
Now if we were to think of, if we were to go to Abhidhamma, this is actually happening at enormous speeds and you can only hold one data of information for every one piece of consciousness.

153
00:16:14,086 --> 00:16:20,758
So if you were, for instance, to put your attention on the eardrum and really, really make it there,

154
00:16:21,464 --> 00:16:30,301
you would eventually arrive at the place where you're not hearing anything, but feeling the pressure of air on the eardrum.

155
00:16:32,966 --> 00:16:41,702
And even that isn't the singularity with which you can experience consciousness.

156
00:16:42,583 --> 00:16:43,505
Consciousness

157
00:16:43,739 --> 00:17:13,492
in a flash can come like that and when we experience this arising and passing away of moments of consciousness what is interesting is that something was still there when there was no consciousness so this drive of anicca, this drive of impermanence takes us right down to an experience of what is there before something arises

158
00:17:13,777 --> 00:17:42,400
in consciousness and that of course becomes a little gateway into a different way of seeing the world when somebody has such an experience it needn't be a cataclysmic thing but it has a systemic effect because that insight now begins to change attitude

159
00:17:42,717 --> 00:17:44,398
So that's the second on the noble path.

160
00:17:45,098 --> 00:17:52,267
And then it begins to express itself by the way we speak and what we do and how we behave and in our livelihoods.

161
00:17:52,287 --> 00:17:53,288
So it comes down.

162
00:17:53,327 --> 00:18:06,019
It's a systemic process which may take time because an insight of that nature, an insight, a deep insight of that nature, has to be matured.

163
00:18:06,059 --> 00:18:08,623
It has to be...

164
00:18:10,325 --> 00:18:38,576
digested and that can take some time and it depends upon the sharpness or the depth of that seeing which will affect the person right the second process the second thing that the self does is presuming itself to be this body the self what does the self want it just wants to be happy

165
00:18:39,551 --> 00:18:42,355
Therefore, it seeks happiness in this form.

166
00:18:46,157 --> 00:18:51,363
And in seeking happiness in this form, every time happiness comes up, it tries to maintain it, to hold it.

167
00:18:51,563 --> 00:18:53,243
And that's what we mean by attachment.

168
00:18:54,305 --> 00:18:59,109
It becomes a psychological dependency for establishing happiness.

169
00:19:00,750 --> 00:19:02,952
And anything that upsets that, of course, you have to get rid of.

170
00:19:02,972 --> 00:19:03,534
You have to shoot.

171
00:19:04,013 --> 00:19:05,275
You have to destroy immediately.

172
00:19:05,675 --> 00:19:08,377
So you can maintain your sense of happiness.

173
00:19:08,662 --> 00:19:12,768
Now, when we ask ourselves, when I say I'm happy, what am I referring to?

174
00:19:13,709 --> 00:19:15,811
Am I referring to a physical sensation?

175
00:19:16,633 --> 00:19:22,101
Would I scream touching my tongue just on a very hot day when I really want it?

176
00:19:22,401 --> 00:19:31,834
Does the actual sensation of ice cream on the tongue, do we consider that to be happiness or just a pleasant taste on the tongue?

177
00:19:33,721 --> 00:19:40,250
When I talk about happiness, do I mean the thought of an ice cream, which may bring up certain other qualities?

178
00:19:40,309 --> 00:19:44,976
But is the thought itself, the sequence of thoughts, is that happiness?

179
00:19:46,157 --> 00:19:50,784
As I'm eating the ice cream and my head is saying, this is really good Italian ice cream.

180
00:19:53,448 --> 00:19:57,472
If I say that to myself, is that line of thought what I call happiness?

181
00:19:59,455 --> 00:20:02,579
Or is happiness the mental state we're in?

182
00:20:02,813 --> 00:20:04,635
especially the emotional state.

183
00:20:05,517 --> 00:20:07,480
In other words, it's a feeling state, isn't it?

184
00:20:07,539 --> 00:20:08,662
It's a state of the heart.

185
00:20:09,262 --> 00:20:19,017
When my heart feels happy and I experience the heart being happy, whatever might be the proximate cause, such as ice cream, that's when I say I'm happy.

186
00:20:19,678 --> 00:20:21,461
So now I become intoxicated.

187
00:20:22,142 --> 00:20:30,755
My whole life becomes a search for things that are going to bring about this mental state, this happiness.

188
00:20:32,176 --> 00:20:32,297
Right?

189
00:20:33,154 --> 00:20:37,060
Now, it's beginning to see the aftermath of that.

190
00:20:37,761 --> 00:20:43,530
That once I'm attached to something, while I'm enjoying things, fine, what's the problem?

191
00:20:44,251 --> 00:20:45,614
It's what happens afterwards.

192
00:20:46,154 --> 00:20:47,477
The craving that comes.

193
00:20:48,218 --> 00:20:51,583
The sort of dependency, the addiction.

194
00:20:52,223 --> 00:20:54,267
At worst, of course, you've got drug addicts.

195
00:20:54,287 --> 00:20:57,092
But we're all addicted to some extent.

196
00:20:58,153 --> 00:21:00,596
And then there's the grief when you lose what you have.

197
00:21:00,813 --> 00:21:02,454
And there's the fear of loss anyway.

198
00:21:03,016 --> 00:21:05,558
So you have to take an insurance policy.

199
00:21:05,578 --> 00:21:07,642
And then there's the frustration where you don't get what you want.

200
00:21:08,282 --> 00:21:09,203
And then there's boredom.

201
00:21:09,904 --> 00:21:14,431
And this society refuses to connect boredom with excitement.

202
00:21:14,851 --> 00:21:15,932
Refuses to do so.

203
00:21:16,794 --> 00:21:17,914
I had a program on boredom.

204
00:21:18,095 --> 00:21:20,137
It said nothing about that connection at all.

205
00:21:21,906 --> 00:21:51,339
boredom is that state when you're no longer in that happy state that things give you so the same thing like an ice cream might be absolutely wonderful and when somebody says would you like another you say well like i've had enough it might of course be a physical thing but you've had enough ice cream but the fact is that if you keep eating ice cream all the time you get fed up with it because it's not giving you the same buzz so there's an inbuilt obsolescence there's an inbuilt uh

206
00:21:52,551 --> 00:22:22,136
process in pleasure whereby it loses its tang and that's the same with relationships you get bored occasionally I mean you all know that you get fed up you get frustrated and then when they threaten to leave you oh god it's fearful so the whole gamut of human suffering is all to do with this relationship we have with the world that we experience right

